Why USB-C requires CC pins
A USB-C source will not turn on VBUS unless it sees:
A valid Rd on CC1 or CC2
A 2-pin connector:
Has no CC pins
So a compliant charger may never provide power
(Some ‚Äúdumb‚Äù chargers always supply 5 V, but this is unreliable.)

| Function            | N-FET (low-side)            | P-FET (high-side)          |
| ------------------- | --------------------------- | -------------------------- |
| Switch location     | Ground side                 | Positive side              |
| Source connected to | GND                         | +V                         |
| Gate turns ON when  | HIGH                        | LOW                        |
| Current path        | Load ‚Üí Drain ‚Üí Source ‚Üí GND | +V ‚Üí Source ‚Üí Drain ‚Üí Load |
| Control simplicity  | Very simple                 | Simple (logic-level OK)    |

