Should you choose MCP3208 B or C package?

C is half the price.

The MCP3208 family is offered in two accuracy classes: B and C. The datasheet
specifies INL = ¬±1 LSB for MCP3204/3208‚ÄìB and INL = ¬±2 LSB for C.

At 12 bits an LSB = VREF / 4096. Example: with VREF = 3.3 V,
LSB ‚âà 3.3 / 4096 ‚âà 0.805 mV ‚Üí ¬±1 LSB ‚âà ¬±0.805 mV, ¬±2 LSB ‚âà ¬±1.61 mV.

Raw ADC numbers (12-bit MCP3208, VREF = 3.3 V)
- LSB = VREF / 4096 = 0.000805664 V = 0.8057 mV.
- Counts across 0‚Ä¶0.8 V = 0.8 / 0.000805664 ‚âà 993 counts.
- Counts per mm = 993 / 3.5 ‚âà 283.7 counts/mm.
- Travel per count (1 LSB) = 3.5 / 993 ‚âà 0.003525 mm ‚âà 3.53 ¬µm.

(So each ADC step corresponds to ~3.5 micrometres of key travel.)

Difference between B and C grades
- MCP3208‚ÄìB INL spec ‚âà ¬±1 LSB; ‚ÄìC ‚âà ¬±2 LSB (typical datasheet split).
- The practical difference between B and C is therefore about 1 LSB (i.e. C can
  be ~1 LSB worse than B in worst case).
- 1 LSB = 0.8057 mV ‚Üí in displacement that‚Äôs ~0.00353 mm = 3.53 ¬µm.
- So B vs C worst-case difference ‚âà ¬±3.5 ¬µm (and C‚Äôs worst-case error could be
  ~¬±7 ¬µm if you compare absolute limits).

3.5 ¬µm (micrometres) is tiny compared with mechanical tolerances, key wobble,
switch spring hysteresis, sensor noise, connector tolerances and human
perception.

Choose C package.

----------------------------------------------------------------------

Bypass capacitor for MCP3208

* ‚ÄúBypass capacitor‚Äù (also called ‚Äúdecoupling capacitor‚Äù) is a small capacitor placed between the chip‚Äôs supply voltage pin (VDD) and ground (GND). Its job is to **filter out high-frequency noise** or transients on the power rail ‚Äî preventing them from upsetting the ADC‚Äôs internal analog circuitry. ([Analog Devices][2])
* The bypass capacitor should go between **VDD** (power supply pin) and **ground**. ([DigiKey][1])
* Choose a small-value **ceramic capacitor** (e.g. 1 ¬µF, X5R/X7R dielectric) ‚Äî good for high-frequency decoupling.
* Connect the ‚Äú‚Äì‚Äù side of the cap to the same ground net/plane that covers **both** the analog ground (AGND) and digital ground (DGND) of the MCP3208.

